## RAHULA MEDITATION

Venerable Rahula, early in the morning, put on his robes and, carrying his
bowl and outer robe, went into Savatthi for alms following behind the Teacher.

Teacher: "Rahula, any form whatsoever that is past, present, or future;
Internal or external.
Blatant or subtle.
Common or sublime.
Far or near.
Every form is to be seen as it actually is with true discernment as:
'This is mine. This is my self. This is what I am.'

Rahula: Just form, O Blessed One? Just form, O One Well-gone?

Teacher: Rahula, develop the meditation of mindfulness of in-&-out
breathing. The meditation of mindfulness of in-&-out breathing, when developed
& pursued, is of great fruit, of great benefit.

Rahula: "How is mindfulness of in-&-out breathing to be developed & pursued
so as to be of great fruit, of great benefit?"

Teacher: "Rahula, any form whatsoever that is past, present, or future;
internal or external; blatant or subtle; common or sublime; far or near:
every form is to be seen as it actually is with true discernment as:

'This is mine. This is my self. This is what I am.'

There are these five properties, Rahula.
1. The earth property
2. The water property
3. The fire property
4. The wind property
5. The space property

Rahula: And what is the earth property?

Teacher: The earth property can be either internal or external.

Rahula: What is the internal earth property?

Teacher: Anything internal, within oneself, that's hard, solid, & sustained.

This is called the internal earth property.

Now both the internal earth property & the external earth property are simply
earth property. And that should be seen as it actually is present with
true discernment:

'This is mine, this is me, this is my self.'

When one sees it thus as it actually is present with true discernment, one
becomes satisfied with the earth property and makes the earth property
fade from the mind.

Rahula: And what is the water property?

Teacher: The water property may be either internal or external.

Rahula: What is the internal water property?

Teacher: Anything internal, belonging to oneself, that's water, watery,
& sustained.

This is called the internal water property.

Now both the internal water property & the external water property are simply
water property. And that should be seen as it actually is present with
true discernment:

'This is mine, this is me, this is my self.'

When one sees it thus as it actually is present with true discernment, one
